s. Harsh and punitive public policies that are designed to keep poor women trapped in low wage work are juxtaposed against the actions of those who, together with their allies, have resisted—inspired by a vision of a different world made possible by higher education.Contributing authors discuss the provisions of the 1996 "welfare reform" (PRWORA) Act and the myriad of statewide responses to educational options within the framework of national legislation. In documenting the multiple obstacles and policy restrictions that low income women face, the book also highlights successful state programs, institutional practices, and community-based programs that afford low income women educational opportunities. The afterword summarizes recent legislative developments and makes policy and advocacy recommendations for the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMothersxEducation (Higher)zUnited States. 0aPoor womenxEducation (Higher)zUnited States. 0aWelfare recipientsxEducation (Higher)zUnited States. 4aEducation : Education. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aBjorklund, Stefani A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Sandra S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Sandra S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClarke, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeprez, Luisa Stormer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeprez, Luisa Stormer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeller, Donald E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahn, Peggy, econtributor.4ctb4ht